00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:06.300
It's a very exciting topic.

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:10.350
And afterwards, we will
start the discussion

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:11.965
about electromagnetic waves.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:17.640
So this is the wave equation
which we have been using,

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:19.970
and over the last
few lectures, we

00:01:19.970 --> 00:01:24.150
have been discussing two
specials kinds of solutions--

00:01:24.150 --> 00:01:26.960
the normal modes,
which is actually

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:30.710
standing waves in the
end, which we identified,

00:01:30.710 --> 00:01:32.930
and the progressing
wave solution, which

00:01:32.930 --> 00:01:37.010
is very powerful in
describing the phenomena which

00:01:37.010 --> 00:01:40.160
we are familiar with.

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:42.650
Last time, in the
end of the lecture,

00:01:42.650 --> 00:01:47.370
we were discussing about
an interesting example,

00:01:47.370 --> 00:01:51.210
which involves two
strings in the system.

00:01:51.210 --> 00:01:57.440
One essentially in the left-hand
side have mass per unit length,

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:02.720
rho l equals to rho 1, and
right-hand side one is thicker,

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:06.070
and therefore, the mass
per unit length, rho,

00:02:06.070 --> 00:02:09.199
is larger, which
is called rho 2.

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:11.450
What we did last
time is to assume

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:15.260
that we have a progressing
wave, which essentially

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:16.220
going into this--

00:02:19.540 --> 00:02:23.240
which essentially first
initiated in the left-hand side

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:29.510
string and it's going towards
the boundary of the two

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:31.040
systems--

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:35.220
the more massive one and
the less massive one.

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:37.590
And see what is going to happen.

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:41.100
And what we actually tried
to describe last time

00:02:41.100 --> 00:02:44.660
is that we actually define
incident wave described

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:51.130
by this fi function,
transmitting wave, ft,

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:54.290
and the refractive wave, fr.

00:02:54.290 --> 00:02:58.310
By using boundary conditions
which we described last time

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:00.860
we can conclude
that there's a fixed

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:09.270
relation between the three
waves equation-- wave functions.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:11.090
What we actually
concluded that last time

00:03:11.090 --> 00:03:18.240
is that fr is proportional to
fi, which is the incident wave

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:22.610
function, by some constant,
which is called r.

00:03:22.610 --> 00:03:24.280
And what is r?

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:29.900
As we solved last time, it's
V2 minus V1 over V1 plus V2,

00:03:29.900 --> 00:03:34.250
which are the velocities of
the first and second string.

00:03:34.250 --> 00:03:39.290
And the transmitted wave, ft,
is actually also proportional

00:03:39.290 --> 00:03:43.950
to the incident wave.

00:03:43.950 --> 00:03:48.950
And the coefficient--
we call it tau--

00:03:48.950 --> 00:03:54.050
to describe the amplitude
of the transmitted wave.

00:03:54.050 --> 00:03:56.900
So what we can do
is the variance.

00:03:56.900 --> 00:04:01.820
So we actually discussed
two examples last time,

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:04.820
plugging in V1 and V2.

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:07.820
And there are two more
examples we can actually

00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:12.110
make use of this equation we
obtained last time to discuss

00:04:12.110 --> 00:04:14.540
what would be the
physics outcome

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:16.290
of this kind of situation.

00:04:16.290 --> 00:04:20.750
So the first example which
we can actually discuss

00:04:20.750 --> 00:04:24.460
is that, OK, now I
have this string.

00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:31.190
Assume, though, they're
connected to a wall.

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:33.530
So this time we can say,
oh, wait, wait, wait, wait

00:04:33.530 --> 00:04:34.030
a second.

00:04:34.030 --> 00:04:35.960
There's only one
string now, right?

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:38.570
But last time we were
solving two strings, right?

00:04:38.570 --> 00:04:42.310
But what I'm doing now
is to treat the wall

00:04:42.310 --> 00:04:44.300
as if it's a string.

00:04:44.300 --> 00:04:47.720
But this wall is really massive.

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:54.080
Therefore, the rho l, or
the mass per unit length,

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:55.410
is really large.

00:04:55.410 --> 00:04:55.910
OK.

00:04:55.910 --> 00:04:59.540
It goes to infinity.

00:04:59.540 --> 00:05:02.570
If that's the case, if
you're set this idea--

00:05:02.570 --> 00:05:06.990
this is still a
two string system--

00:05:06.990 --> 00:05:09.200
then I can now go
ahead and calculate

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:11.510
what will be the velocity.

00:05:11.510 --> 00:05:17.240
The velocity V2 goes to 0.

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:21.340
Then I can go ahead and
plug into my equations.

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:25.610
So we spend a lot of
time in the last lecture

00:05:25.610 --> 00:05:27.650
to obtain those equations.

00:05:27.650 --> 00:05:32.900
And we will find that
if I have V2 goes to 0,

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:36.560
I have r equal to minus 1.

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:40.400
And the tau, which
is actually related

00:05:40.400 --> 00:05:43.010
to the amplitude of
the transmitted wave,

00:05:43.010 --> 00:05:47.070
is equal to 0, which you
can see from this equation.

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:48.590
What does that mean?

00:05:48.590 --> 00:05:51.890
That means once we
solve that question,

00:05:51.890 --> 00:05:57.800
we also know what would be the
outcome of this experiment,

00:05:57.800 --> 00:05:59.090
this physical situation.

00:05:59.090 --> 00:06:02.390
When we have a string
attached to a wall

00:06:02.390 --> 00:06:06.920
and we have an incident wave,
as a function of time, what

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:10.370
is going to happen afterward
is that this wave is

00:06:10.370 --> 00:06:13.930
going to propagate and
hit the wall and get

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:17.210
refracted completely.

00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:21.230
The amplitude ratio is minus 1.

00:06:21.230 --> 00:06:25.280
Therefore, all the
energy is refracted

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:30.800
by the wall in this highly
idealized situation.

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:33.150
So that's kind of interesting.

00:06:33.150 --> 00:06:37.440
The second example is
also very interesting.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:42.740
So if you have a string
attached to a massive ring,

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:51.850
and this ring can go up and down
freely without any friction,

00:06:51.850 --> 00:06:55.750
you can again say, no, no, no,
this is again a single string

00:06:55.750 --> 00:06:57.040
system, right?

00:06:57.040 --> 00:07:00.490
But what I'm going to
argue now is that, OK,

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:05.680
there's another string which is
so light mass per unit length

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:09.340
is close to 0.

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:13.000
So it is actually in the air.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.150
If I do that, what
is going to happen?

00:07:16.150 --> 00:07:21.790
The rho l is going to
go to the limit of 0,

00:07:21.790 --> 00:07:27.070
because the right-hand side
you almost cannot see it.

00:07:27.070 --> 00:07:31.300
And the V2, which
is the velocity

00:07:31.300 --> 00:07:36.130
of the transmitted
wave, goes to infinity.

00:07:36.130 --> 00:07:38.300
If that's the case,
you can then again,

00:07:38.300 --> 00:07:40.930
plugging into this equation
we obtained, and then

00:07:40.930 --> 00:07:46.030
you conclude that r
would be equal to 1

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:50.270
and tau will be equal to 2.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:51.590
So what does that mean?

00:07:51.590 --> 00:07:55.600
This means that if you
have this end, which

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:59.230
is the open end,
attached to a ring which

00:07:59.230 --> 00:08:04.740
can move up and down, then
you get that refraction.

00:08:04.740 --> 00:08:07.280
The amplitude of
the refractive wave

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:11.950
doesn't change, because
i is equal to 1.

00:08:11.950 --> 00:08:16.980
So it's still in the positive
direction we defined.

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:19.060
But now, it goes backward.

00:08:19.060 --> 00:08:22.700
Again, all the energy
is actually refracted,

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:25.000
as you can see
from this equation.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.370
But the curious case is that--

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:33.350
the strangest thing is
that the tau is equal to 2.

00:08:33.350 --> 00:08:35.159
That's kind of strange, right?

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:37.347
Tau is equal to 2.

00:08:37.347 --> 00:08:38.180
What does that mean?

00:08:38.180 --> 00:08:43.840
That means you are going to
predict a transmitted wave

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:49.250
with amplitude exactly the
two times the incident wave,

00:08:49.250 --> 00:08:52.390
and it's going to be propagating
in the right-hand side

00:08:52.390 --> 00:08:55.180
and the speed goes to infinity.

00:08:57.970 --> 00:08:59.070
What does that mean?

00:08:59.070 --> 00:09:02.650
Does that mean the
energy is not conserved?

00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:07.660
Have we found the cure
of the energy crisis?

00:09:07.660 --> 00:09:12.530
Because now-- I can actually
take all those energy.

00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:14.480
I can design this thing,
and then this thing

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:17.290
will bounce around
all over the place.

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:20.180
And that is going
to emit energy.

00:09:20.180 --> 00:09:22.550
Oh my god, we solve
all the problem.

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:25.650
You should be really
excited about it, right?

00:09:25.650 --> 00:09:28.430
No?

00:09:28.430 --> 00:09:33.430
But unfortunately,
rho l goes to 0.

00:09:33.430 --> 00:09:38.540
So there's actually nothing
oscillating out of this system.

00:09:38.540 --> 00:09:43.100
So therefore, there is no
additional energy radiated out

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:44.360
of this system.

00:09:44.360 --> 00:09:45.290
Too bad.

00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:48.530
Go back to work.

00:09:48.530 --> 00:09:49.520
All right.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:52.220
So that's actually what
we discussed last time,

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:54.920
and I hope that
complete the loop.

00:09:54.920 --> 00:10:00.800
And today, before we
actually move to sound wave,

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:04.000
I would like to talk
about, very briefly,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.060
harmonic progressing waves.

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:13.580
So now, we can see that harmonic
progressing wave looks really

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:15.740
beautiful, as you can see here.

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:23.820
And it can be described by a
cosine kx minus omega t plus 5.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:25.600
5 is actually the face.

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:30.620
And you can always write
it in different forms.

00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:33.770
And since we have
learned how to describe

00:10:33.770 --> 00:10:37.670
in general the progressing
wave, this is just to remind you

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:39.880
that, OK, there's
no proper notion

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:43.800
to describe a harmonic
progressing wave.

00:10:47.450 --> 00:10:52.520
So since we have
learned about waves,

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:58.160
which involve oscillation
in the transverse direction.

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:00.540
So basically, we
always say, OK, things

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:05.000
are oscillating up and
down in the case of string.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.990
Before I start, though,
the sound wave, there's

00:11:07.990 --> 00:11:12.830
a different kind of wave
which we can also see

00:11:12.830 --> 00:11:15.480
very often in the daily life.

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:19.220
This is called
longitudinal waves.

00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:25.100
For example, I can have a spring
wave, and I can actually--

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:26.890
imagine I have a spring wave.

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:28.220
And I can do this.

00:11:28.220 --> 00:11:31.250
I oscillate in the
horizontal direction.

00:11:31.250 --> 00:11:37.100
Then that can produce
displacement with respect

00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:39.200
to the equilibrium position.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:43.970
And this kind of behavior
is like a density wave.

00:11:43.970 --> 00:11:46.253
We call it longitudinal waves.

00:11:49.040 --> 00:11:53.640
This is exactly what is
happening with sound wave.

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:55.180
So what is actually sound wave?

00:11:55.180 --> 00:12:00.830
Essentially, a collection
or motion of air molecules.

00:12:00.830 --> 00:12:04.350
And they are actually
oscillating back and forth.

00:12:04.350 --> 00:12:11.840
And we may use that to extend
energy all over the place.

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:15.560
And today we are going to
discuss the sound wave.

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:18.950
And by the way,
just for simplicity,

00:12:18.950 --> 00:12:24.500
because drawing all those dots
really take a lot of time.

00:12:24.500 --> 00:12:27.470
So what we sometimes
do is that, OK,

00:12:27.470 --> 00:12:32.150
we can now draw the pressure,
the amplitude of the pressure,

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:35.260
or the amplitude
of the displacement

00:12:35.260 --> 00:12:39.770
of individual molecules
in the discussion

00:12:39.770 --> 00:12:40.800
as a function of time.

00:12:40.800 --> 00:12:45.190
So if we draw the amplitude
as a function of time

00:12:45.190 --> 00:12:49.310
or as a function of
location, then it

00:12:49.310 --> 00:12:52.830
looks exactly the same as
what we discussed before

00:12:52.830 --> 00:12:56.600
for the transverse waves.

00:12:56.600 --> 00:12:58.550
So just some clarification.

00:12:58.550 --> 00:13:02.370
It's not like the molecules
are going up and down.

00:13:02.370 --> 00:13:05.810
They are going back and
forth, and it's just a matter

00:13:05.810 --> 00:13:08.270
presenting that these are.

00:13:08.270 --> 00:13:12.010
So this is actually an
example of a travelling wave

00:13:12.010 --> 00:13:14.250
in the longitudinal direction.

00:13:14.250 --> 00:13:16.470
And you can see
that it is actually

00:13:16.470 --> 00:13:20.970
the density which is actually
changing as a function of time.

00:13:20.970 --> 00:13:23.450
And as you can
see, it's actually

00:13:23.450 --> 00:13:29.410
traveling at a fixed speed and
going in the right direction

00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:33.460
of the blackboard.

00:13:33.460 --> 00:13:38.110
So those being said,
we can actually

00:13:38.110 --> 00:13:41.780
get started with a
concrete example.

00:13:41.780 --> 00:13:46.400
So I would like to discuss
with you now a system,

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:53.676
which is like you have a tube,
with cross section area, A.

00:13:53.676 --> 00:13:58.850
So A is actually the area
of the cross section.

00:13:58.850 --> 00:14:01.850
And I can now wonder--

00:14:01.850 --> 00:14:07.550
now the physics question I'm
asking is, what would be the--

00:14:07.550 --> 00:14:14.700
what would be the behavior
of the air inside this tube?

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:18.730
So before I go ahead
and solve this problem,

00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:21.450
I need to define and give
you some more information

00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:26.580
about this tube and also the
condition or the environment

00:14:26.580 --> 00:14:29.050
this tube is living in.

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:32.220
So the first information
I would like to give you

00:14:32.220 --> 00:14:38.080
is that the pressure,
the room pressure,

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:42.100
is actually P0 in this example.

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:44.970
So the P0 is actually
the room pressure.

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:51.600
And I can now define coordinates
is the x direction is actually

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:53.910
in the horizontal
direction pointing

00:14:53.910 --> 00:14:56.280
to the right-hand side.

00:14:56.280 --> 00:15:03.630
And now, I can actually try to
describe a small unit volume

00:15:03.630 --> 00:15:09.150
inside the tube by location x.

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:15.180
And the width of this
volume, I call it delta x.

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:23.092
And if I go ahead and prepare
this system and at time, t,

00:15:23.092 --> 00:15:25.890
something is happening
to this system--

00:15:25.890 --> 00:15:29.960
so now, you need length.

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:32.210
You need volume,
I was discussing.

00:15:32.210 --> 00:15:38.150
This get displaced with respect
to the equilibrium position.

00:15:38.150 --> 00:15:40.730
So that means, assuming
that something happened

00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:46.210
at the t equal to t, the left
inside edge of the volume

00:15:46.210 --> 00:15:50.760
is shifted toward a positive
direction, which is described

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:54.540
by wave function psi x.

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:57.510
And the position of
the right-hand side

00:15:57.510 --> 00:16:06.240
edge of this volume is shifted
to side x plus delta x.

00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:09.750
So something happened
to this system.

00:16:09.750 --> 00:16:12.570
We can also say
that-- we can also

00:16:12.570 --> 00:16:16.230
describe this system, the
pressure of this system,

00:16:16.230 --> 00:16:18.030
by P function.

00:16:18.030 --> 00:16:22.230
P of x is actually
equal to P0, which

00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:25.860
is actually room pressure--

00:16:25.860 --> 00:16:29.190
P0 is the baseline
room pressure--

00:16:29.190 --> 00:16:39.500
plus some kind of displacement
in pressure, psi P.

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:45.010
So now we describe the pressure
acting on the left inside edge

00:16:45.010 --> 00:16:49.470
of the small unit volume,
and the right-hand side,

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:52.000
you can also do the same thing.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:59.530
P of x plus delta x will
be equal to P0 plus psi P,

00:16:59.530 --> 00:17:02.450
describing the
displacement or how

00:17:02.450 --> 00:17:07.300
offset the pressure is as a
function of x but now evaluated

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:10.780
at x plus delta x.

00:17:10.780 --> 00:17:17.329
So once we have all of
those elements defined--

00:17:17.329 --> 00:17:19.000
these are essentially
just a copy

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:24.280
of what I have in the slide
and those are a reminder here--

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:30.310
now, we can actually calculate
the motion of all the molecules

00:17:30.310 --> 00:17:38.670
in this volume, because I have
pressure, I have displacement.

00:17:38.670 --> 00:17:41.770
The displacement is
described by psi,

